    <h2>The Proposal</h2>
    <h3>how he popped the question</h3>

    <p>If there was a Mr. Chicago pageant, I'm pretty sure Conrad would win by a landslide. He lives and breathes this city and believe me when I say that it's no small compliment when he decided I could be an honorary Chicagoan. So imagine my surprise when he told me that he hadn't done a bunch of Chicago-y things like go up to the top of the Hancock or have deep dish at Gino's East. And so began what we like to call our Tourist Date Series - days spent exploring Navy Pier, strolling down Michigan Avenue, one way, way, way overdue trip to Portillo's, and countless visits to Museum Campus (one of our first dates was at the Field Museum). </p>

    <p>Anyway, 2014 had been an exceptionally busy year for us - so many of our friends were getting married, he was moving, and we had both started new jobs. Conrad was making a big fuss about having a weekend for just the two of us and when it just so happened that everyone was &ldquo;busy&rdquo; on September 6, we seized the day for our own to have another tourist date.</p>

    <p>We started the day with brunch in the South Loop and because it was so gorgeous outside, we had planned to meander down Michigan Avenue. But while I was putting together a mental shopping list, Conrad instead steered us towards Museum Campus. The ramps in front of the Field Museum have some of the best views of the city and we paused there to take a picture and enjoy the sights. Conrad gestured to the skyline and started to reminisce about our time together - how we met, the life we were building together, and how happy we made each other. The next thing I knew, he went down on one knee and asked me to marry him. I, of course, said yes. </p>

    <p>And then did a little dance : )</p>
